A small match stick crossbow. It can shoot matches, cu-tips, and more!

To build the Match Stick Crossbow, you need dental floss, hot glue (EDIT: You can also use super glue for better effects), and 2 hair barrettes.
1). Hot glue the handle to the body. (example 1 - 2)
2). Remove the center from the hair barrettes. You can discard them. (example 3-4)
3). Glue the hair barrettes to the front of the cross bow. (example 5)
4). To reinforce the connection, glue the front on the hair barrettes. (example 6)
5). Double knot some floss on the end of a hair beret, than hot glue it down. (example 7-8)
6). Do the same to the other hair barrettes, make sure that the floss is tight, the tighter it is the farther it will shoot.

To Shoot:
Pull the floss to the back so it clips in. (example 9) Next put the match in the slit. (example 10) Aim than use your thumb to release the floss and fire the match. (example 11-12)

title: Trumpet Adaptive Device by Caitlin Driver

description.text:
This adaptive device was designed for a boy without fingers on his left hand who plays a Bach Student Trumpet, model TR300.

The system is made up of five components;
(1) MAIN - surrounds and snaps onto the left side of the valves
(2) BOTTOM - slides over the base of the valves and main, snaps into place
(3) DOVETAIL - connects to the palm via two 1/8" barrel diameter Chicago screws, slides in and out of the main valve surround
(4) PALM - connects to both the dovetail and gauntlet via two 1/8" barrel diameter Chicago screws
(5) GAUNTLET - connects to the palm via two 1/8" barrel Chicago screws, slotted for Velcro attachment to arm

You can download the original size, built for a 10 year old, OR you can download scalable versions of the DOVETAIL, PALM, and GAUNTLET.

There are two different versions of the PALM - one that is full and must be printed on its "top," and one that can be printed in two parts and joined together with acetone or other adhesive method.

The trumpet with MAIN and BOTTOM attached, fits perfectly into the Bach trumpet case for easy storage after use.

This device was created by Caitlin Driver during her 2015 Summer Fellowship, funded by the Enable Community Foundation, in the University of Wisconsin Milwaukee’s Digital Craft Research Lab.

For more information on this device visit Caitlin's blog: http://digitalfabricationanddesign.blogspot.com/search/label/e-NABLE

description.text:
Feeling generous and want to support my design work? Visit my Myminifactory page and leave a tip, It would be greatly appreciated.
https://www.myminifactory.com/users/EthanNewhouse

This is a two piece clip on fan duct to mount 40mm fans to the stock Robo3D R1 Hexagon hot end and X-carriage. Ducts fit front and back of X-carriage and are very solid (no wobbling like other fan ducts).

Print the duct with the fan mounting surface on the build platform. Print the clip with either side of it on the build platform so that it forms a J when viewed from above ( the clip will break if not printed in this orientation). I printed at .2 layer height and used CA glue AKA "super glue" to attach the clip to the duct. It is a tight fit, and may require some filing/sanding to fit properly. Please provide feedback if there is anything that you feel should be done differently. I am always open to productive commentary. Happy printing!

Two part epoxy
Alligator clips and wire.

Use pictures to assemble. Solder a short wire to the fender washer so it will go through the hole in the top printed part. Not necessary to feed through the bottom part. Hook up to digital input on your stepper control and setup the port to be z-zero. measure the actual height of the block and setup Mach3 to offset the height of the block. Then when you need to zero your z, connect one lead to the tool/bit and the other lead to the block wire.

description.text:
I published this on the RepRap buliders blob http://builders.reprap.org/ some days before and was asked to publish it here also.. so here is my post from the Builders blog... nspired by a paper from Kruth et al. (2005, Benchmarking of different SLS/SLM processes as rapid manufacturing techniques) I also designed a benchmark model for the RepRap. It looks quite random but by printing it you can check whether your RepRap prints geometrically correct. I included the following features: -vertical holes for M3, M4, M8 screws
-vertical hexagons suitable for M3, M4 M8 nuts
-horizontal teardrops M3, M4 M8 and hexagons for suitable nuts
-sharp edges with angles of 15, 30 and 45 deg
-thin walls 0.5mm, 1,0mm, 1.5mm and 2mm horizontally and vertically
-stair effect at sloped walls with angles of 15, 30, 45, 60 and 80 deg
-round corners, radius 4mm to 16mm
-gear teeth with 2mm wide teeth
-in addition to this, you can also check perpendicularity and parallelism of your printed objects, which were the general intentions of designing a benchmark. You can download both the STL and the AoI file from SourceForge /mendel/mechanics/test-parts Printing it took about two hours, so why not watching a fancy movie while your RepRap prints its benchmark. The very first version included a complete horizontal hexagon for M8 nuts, but apparently this made the object to big in height, so I just cut it off, leaving just a small offset ;) The gear teeth were not built as expected but as a round corner with a bubbled rim. I am also missing the 0.5mm thin walls. The 1.5mm walls consist of only two parallel strings and are not solid, there is a small gap between them in both directions.

There is also a new precision setting to adjust the complexity/accuracy (number of vertices).

The trouble with 3D printing a ball bearing is that spheres don't adhere to the 45 degree rule, so they tend to print poorly, or if metal balls are used instead, then the bearing requires assembly. This is a new kind of bearing that can only be manufactured by 3D printing and comes preassembled.

It is a planetary gearset and functions like a cross between a needle bearing and a thrust bearing. No cage is required to keep the rollers in place, because their gearing keeps them perfectly spaced. The gears are all herringbone, which is why it cannot be disassembled and also why it can act as a thrust bearing. If you're wondering how well a 3D printed bearing could work under load, please check out this video: http://youtu.be/ZghwSBiM0sU

This design is fully parametric and made to be adjusted in the Customizer app to whatever you need.
This is an expanded version of: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:53451
Thanks to emmett for sharing the original version.

The key to any bearing is the tolerance between the moving parts. Since this is printed all at once, you want the minimum tolerance possible, where any less would fuse the parts together. It may require a fair bit of torque to break it free at first. It's designed to fit onto the standard English hex size for screwdriver bits, so you can use a tool to help turn it. Running it in a drill for a few minutes helps to smooth out the rotation.

You can adjust the tolerance in Customizer if you need. You can also change the dimensions, numbers of planets, numbers of teeth, etc. Normal gears use a small pressure angle in order to transmit torque, but here I use a large pressure angle so that they transmit force better (hence why they look more pointed than usual). Your chosen number of sun gear teeth is approximate because planetary gearboxes turn out to be quite constrained in terms of what tooth numbers will fit.

title: Robo 3D Printbed Mounting Bracket with Aztech Webcam Mount Plate

description.text:
This is a modular mounting design. The mounting bracket attaches the Robo3D print bed and provides a mount point for any properly keyed mount plate. The dimensions for the key are provided in the attached drawings.

The plate I've included is for an Aztech WIPC302 camera, but a new plate could easily be crafted for a smartphone or some other device.

The mount bracket is slim enough that more than one may be used on a single edge of the print bed.

(Please, Click the like button if you like it!)

8/16/15 - I just noticed a problem with the design you will want to look out for. It's pretty ridiculous to have missed this early on, but for my Aztech camera, I realized that the extruder carriage is hitting the camera during the auto leveling step. It doesn't seem to have messed up the prints, but obviously this is undesirable. So, whichever mounting plate you use, just be sure that you check clearance. I'll make some design adjustments when I have time.

I use a Robo 3D with this ABS by Matterhackers.

I've used PLA on similar mount brackets in the past and they easily broke under stress.

Note that each part has a small cylindrical indentation on one face. This is the face that should be downward onto the print-bed. This will allow for strength in the appropriate stress points.

The YouTube video here shows the assembly concept:
https://youtu.be/Pkc3rAV3yMo

description.text:
Badges? We don't need no stinking badges!

But if you do, here are some.

This summer we have had nerf wars with all the neighborhood kids. It has often ended up as a 22 person free for all, but when they wanted to play capture the flag, teams were formed and requests were made. How could I say 'no.'

Printed one team emblem and about 8 badges (scaled down 50%) for each team. Instant success. I keep printing them out and they keep disappearing.

Next Up is family Geocoins for our Geocaching

1] Choice a color for your teams
2] Print each full sized Coin in the filament color for each team - This is their 'flag.'
3] (optional) Scale down 50%
4] Print out badges for teams in the team colors (make sure to print a couple extra just in case.)
5] (optional) Hot glue a safety-pin to the back of the badge, or drill a hole in it and put it on a string.
6] Watch the fun.

For ages 6 to 106.

My first real big 3d printing project.

This is the starts of a dragon's head wall trophy. Here is the head of Níðhöggr (Nidhogger or Nidhogg - meaning Malice Striker) the wyrm. The dragon that, according to norse mythology, gnaws at a roots of the world tree of Yggdrasil.

Use this to hold your sketching pencils, tools or simply collect PLA scraps and trimmings.

I got tired of sweeping PLA bits off the table, and then having to sweep the floor. This slide-out tray catches everything and with a brush (or piece of tissue paper) I can sweep it all neatly into a small bin or envelope for disposal.

All 3D printed parts except for the 3-inch electrical trunk cap and screws.

***** UPDATE 9 Oct 2015: Centre bracket and clip added, for long installations.

You will need:
2 x M320 screws (M312mm is minimum recommended)
4 to 6 wood/ metal screws to secure the brackets under your table
** Mine is plastic and steel so I used metal screws
1 length of 3-inch electrical cable trunk (just the cap)
2 x M3 Washers (optional)

Print:
2 brackets (1 left, 1 right)
2 Clips (1 left, 1 right -- 3 types to choose from: CLOSED left/right end or open-ended). Print open-ended for the side where you will sweep the scraps off. Or print both with closed ends if you want to use it as a drawer.

Installation:

  1. Mark and mount 1 bracket onto table underside.
  2. Slide in clip and secure with M3 screw (washer optional) - do not tighten fully, this holds the clip in place but allows sliding action.
  3. Repeat for other side.
  4. Measure distance between inner-most edge of both clips.
  5. Cut trunking cap, insert.
    ** If your strip is short and both clips are closed, you may want to perform step 5 before fastening the M3 screws on the clips (step 2)

For reference, my set up is 89cm wide.

These are some small sand molds that let you make tessellations on the beach.

The kite and dart were invented by Roger Penrose and let you fill a plane aperiodically. http://mathworld.wolfram.com/PenroseTiles.html

Rep-tiles are shapes that can be tiled in a way to make a larger version of themselves. This means they are also capable of filling a plane, as you can always make an exponentially larger Rep-tile from the one you just made. What Rep-tile is more appropriate for the beach than a fish? There's some great information here. https://overlordoftheuberferal.wordpress.com/tag/tessellation/

All the models are equipped with air holes that will help break the suction that when you're trying to demold. It has plagued sandcastle makers for generations. The holes are positioned so that you can place a finder over them during filling, although wet sand isn't likely to fall through anyway.

The secutity cap is optional and can be omitted if you don't have to change angle often.

  • Reduced the diameter of the portion of the bracket which has to be magnetized to the external support
  • Added a version with no security compatibility to reduce the space

3 - print magnet holder and slide a 8x8mm magnet in its target hole (don't glue). Beware that the magnet is set in opposition with the one in cam support.
4 - slide magnet holder in cam support and keep the to pieces compressed with your fingers.
5 - insert the two compressed pieces in horz support and, as the arm of cam support is in front off the hors support groove, rotate the bracket to secure the system.

comments.text:
Hi,
I am sorry, but I do not know the reason for material curling up. Might be it could be helpful to adjust the amount of retraction in case of layer change (if your slicer supports that feature. I use Simplify 3D for slicing ). Another reason could be the print temperature or the influence of the cooling fan.
Bulldog XL:
I wanted to change to 1.75 mm material to be prepared for a later upgrade to a dual extruder (from E3D), which was not available at that time, but was announced. I tried to modify the stock extruder to work with 1.75 mm material; this attempt failed.
So my choice was a Bulldog extruder. On the other way a dual extruder solution with two stock extruders is not possible due to their size.
The difference between a Bulldog and a Bulldog XL is: the Bulldog XL has a gear box (5:1) included, which is recommended for 3 mm material. As I heard, the normal Bulldog without gearbox would be good enough for 1.75mm material, but please - get informations from the web yourself.
The Bulldog without gearbox does not match to this construction. You would need a different mount.
If you want to save money, just look for other extruder solutions - there are a lot of them in Thingiverse, but they all need to be adapted to the K8200.
In my construction I wanted to achieve a compact solution with the effect of (almost) direct driven hotends. The weight of the all metal Bulldogs do not matter, because they only move in Z-direction which has no influence to the dynamics of the system.

comments.text:
Hi,
I have good experience with the dual extruder from E3D. I ordered the Legends Pack, wich includes both the Chimera and the Cyclops.
I tested both and I prefer the Chimera. With the Chimera you are more flexible. You can use different temperatures when using different materials in one session. The small footprint (distance between nozzles is just 18 mm) does not restrict the printing area very much.
I am printing ABS only (at 260 /110 degrees) and there are collision problems with the unused nozzle. If they are adjusted to one level, there is no difference between a single or a dual extruder, because - if the printed material warps, it will cause collision problems with a single and a dual extruder as well.
Bulldog XL:
First I upgraded my K8200 with an E3D v6 and a Bulldog XL, because i had a lot of problems with the stock parts. Yes, the Bulldog XL is no low-prized extruder, but in my opinion it ist worth its prize. I have had good experience with the single extruder solution, and therefore I wanted to keep them with the dual extruder solution.
Finally I can recommend this constellation, although it is expensive. Perhaps Santa Claus can do something for you.
Good luck

DISASTER SCENARIO No.2 You pick up your pair of trousers/pants and "Oh no!" the top button of the button fly has broken! You've already salvaged any other buttons you could from unneeded pockets, etc - you really don't have a button to use! Worry not - you can very quickly print a replacement, sew it on, and be out of the door in under 15 minutes! (Depending on your hand-sewing speed.)

Emergency button for replacing broken or lost buttons on clothing.
2cm diameter - appropriate for button flies.
Very quick to print - under 5 minutes.
Doesn't bend, flex or snap - tested as the top button on a pair of pants for 2 weeks of wearing and counting.
Safe* in the washing machine and tumble dryer. *So far - YMMV, but the average tumble dryer heats to 175C, and while PLA softens at 50C, the extrusion temp is closer to 230C.

Print with or without a raft - the raft version will take longer to trim than it will to print the button, but printing raftless can result in slightly 'closed' button-eyes. Print normally. I recommend a quick 30 second going over with a piece of sandpaper on the edge (if you print raftless) to get rid of the slightly sharp edge where the plastic touched the print base. If you are nervous about putting these through your washing/drying cycle, pop one or two in an old tied off sock, or small fabric bag, and throw them in the next cycle. The bag/sock will stop the plastic from melting everywhere, if it does fail for some reason. I've had no issues, personally. comments.text: Cool model, printing it now. Took me TEN tries before I realized that your first layer is the mouth only, and sadly I can't get Cura to lay a support for only one layer. We'll see how it turns out and I'll update this in the morning when it's done.
comments.author: Davedwin

comments.text: Came out nice! Thank you for a cool model. I gave my 13 year old daughter the option of a few that I printed with this one, and she chose the minion. With some sanding I don't think the mouth will be an issue like with chorobe. ;-)
comments.author: Davedwin

comments.text: Mine was completely filled for the mouth slot.  You can't really cut it well with a knife either.  I tried using a dremel tool but it messed it up completely.  The mouth is less than 1mm in height.  I think that tolerance is too tight for my da Vinci Jr to handle.  I will edit it tinkercad and reprint with a bigger opening.  Hopefully that will work better.
comments.author: chorobe
